cs.CR, cs.NI, cs.DC, cs.IT, cs.SY 

This paper deals with the security and communication aspects of wireless sensor networks, which are typically studied in the computer science sub-categories of cryptography (cs.CR), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC), information theory (cs.IT), and systems and control (cs.SY). The focus on secure communication and key predistribution schemes makes cs.CR and cs.NI the most likely categories, followed by cs.DC and cs.IT, which deal with the distributed nature of sensor networks and the reliability of wireless links. The use of mathematical analysis and probability theory to derive a zero-one law for secure k-connectivity also suggests a possible fit with cs.SY.
